    {
      "id": "eaf5266c3b7ea8c28188a6c9dcc676cfe6677783",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-05 02:45:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (21 inline comments)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3d7a0f54735004c85949c03661b4e4daa745ded2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-05 03:00:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Alex Zhuravlev\t\t1:38 AM\n> at the moment I'm a bit confused this is implemented in OSD.. I'd expect big LFSCK to do this.\n\nWhat's the advantage of rebuild LAST_ID via up layer LFSCK instead of low layer OI scrub?\n\nIn fact, the initial OI scrub can detect some crashed LAST_ID when mount, then it is reasonable to give it to normal OI scrub to rebuild the LAST_ID. But if want the initial OI scrub to notify up layer LFSCK to do that, then there is not proper way/interface yet.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5f5e2a54511d0e9cfa28a55d60850f16a0506c16",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-05 04:07:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthe advantage is that this recovery mechanism would apply to any backend. and again, having similar logic in the same place (LFSCK) surely makes sense. the only reason for OI scrub to be part of OSD is OI which is internal to OSD ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3c471376f8037e06a51d68d2cbe35a438df43d4c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-05 08:46:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Alex Zhuravlev\t\t12:07 PM\n> the advantage is that this recovery mechanism would apply to any backend. and again, having similar logic in the same place (LFSCK) surely makes sense. the only reason for OI scrub to be part of OSD is OI which is internal to OSD ?\n\nI agree with that the rebuild LAST_ID should work for any backend. But if want to do that in LFSCK instead of OSD, then we need to resolve some implementation  troubles: during the LFSCK scanning, it may find the LAST_ID crashed, so it needs to update the LAST_ID if it found more higher oid in the <seq>. If each later scanned is higher than its former (for the case LAST_ID file lost), then it will cause the LAST_ID to be updated for each object scanned. That is almost cannot be accepted. So we still need some work in OSD to process such cases, which may need some new APIs or parameters for the LFSCK to notify and control OSD's behaviour.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "e7e850e20dbdafe7e11ffdb2ddb8707599d4dd56",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-05 08:54:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nnot sure I follow well. LFSCK needs to scan objects on underlying device. LFSCK should be able to tell whether specific object belongs to MDT or OST (remember we're developing UT). when LFSCK meet OST object it could corresponding LAST_ID (<seq>:0) and start to track it on its own and if needed  update. I'm not sure why this can't be accepted.\n\nbut more interesting thing is how it's supposed to stay consistent and making sense while both parties touch it (OFD + recovery).\n\nalso, I'm not sure how it can be recovered at mount. can you clarify a bit?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c85bebccc19177df1448bde493a0203a71576620",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-08 07:43:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Abandoned\n\nThe repairing logic will be moved to up layer within LFSCK framework.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "32bb2e7915e276e49de4dc205a92253b25e2cd5f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-08 15:58:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nFan Yong, to answer one of your earlier questions - the \"fid\" xattr (\"struct filter_fid_old\" today) was first added in Lustre 1.6, and was only changed in Lustre 2.4 to be smaller and move the \"self FID\" into LMA.  However, the \"fid\" xattr was only added to objects when they are first modified, unlike the \"lma\" xattr that is added when they are created.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    }
  ],
